A. P. J. Abdul Kalam was the 11th President of India from 2002 to 2007. A career scientist turned reluctant politician, Kalam was born and raised in Rameswaram, Tamil Nadu, and studied physics and aerospace engineering. He spent the next four decades as a scientist and science administrator, mainly at the Defence Research and Development Organisation (DRDO) and Indian Space Research Organisation (ISRO) and was intimately involved in India's civilian space program and military missile development efforts. He thus came to be known as the Missile Man of India for his work on the development of ballistic missile and launch vehicle technology. He also played a pivotal organizational, technical, and political role in India's Pokhran-II nuclear tests in 1998, the first since the original nuclear test by India in 1974. Kalam was elected as the 11th President of India in 2002, with the support of the Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP), the Indian National Congress (INC), and other opposition parties. He took office on 25 July 2002, and was re-elected for a second term in 2007. He was the first scientist to occupy the office of President of India, and is thus popularly referred to as the People's President.

Stereophonics released their debut album, Word Gets Around, in 1997, which was certified double platinum by the British Phonographic Industry (BPI). Other? in 2005, and Pull the Pin in 2007. The band's fifth studio album, Scream Above the Sounds, was released in 2009, followed by Graffiti on the Train in 2013, and Keep the Village Alive in 2015. Stereophonics have sold over 10 million albums worldwide.

She is known for her two best-selling novels, The Fountainhead and Atlas Shrugged, and for developing a philosophical system she named Objectivism. In 1957, she published her best-known work, the novel Atlas Shrugged. Afterward, she turned to non-fiction to promote her philosophy, publishing her own magazines and releasing several collections of essays until her death in 1982. Rand advocated reason as the only means of acquiring knowledge and rejected faith and religion. She supported rational and ethical egoism, and rejected ethical altruism. In politics, she condemned the initiation of force as immoral and opposed collectivism and statism, instead supporting limited government and laissez-faire capitalism, which she believed was the only social system that protected individual rights. Rand promoted romantic realism in fiction and advocated individualism and rational and ethical egoism in her non-fiction writing. She rejected the idea that art should be a vehicle for propaganda and that moral judgments can be separated from aesthetic judgments. Rand's novels have a large following worldwide and have significant influence on the modern libertarian movement and on American conservatism. She has been a major influence on the American right, including figures such as Alan Greenspan, Antony Fisher, Milton Friedman, George Gilder, John Hospers, Ludwig von Mises, Robert Nozick, Murray Rothbard, and Thomas Sowell. She has also been a major influence on the American left, including figures such as Barbara Branden, Chris Matthew Sciabarra, and Michael Shermer.
